Let $\delta \theta$ be the difference of $\theta$ between two rings corresponding to two wavelengths limiting the visible range, i.e. to wavelengths of $0.4 \mu \mathrm{m}$ (violet) and $0.8 \mu \mathrm{m}$ (red), respectively. The difference in the refraction indexes at these wavelengths is $n_{\mathrm{v}}-n_{\mathrm{r}}=\delta n=0.02(n-1)$.

Logarithmically differentiating both sides of equation (14) gives



$$
\frac{\sin \theta \times \delta \theta}{\cos \theta}=\frac{\delta n}{n}
\tag{15}
$$

Corresponding to the pressure of the radiator $P=6 \mathrm{~atm}$ we have from 4.2. the values $\theta_{\pi}=3.2^{\circ}, \quad n=1.00162$.

Putting approximately $\tan \theta=\theta$ and $n=1$, we get $\delta \theta=\frac{\delta n}{\theta}=0.033^{\circ}$.

The general solution of (14) is :

$$
C(t)=K \exp \left(-\frac{u t}{W}\right)+\frac{M}{L H u}
\tag{15}
$$

From the initial condition $C(0)=0$, we can deduce :

$$
C(t)=\frac{M}{L H u}\left[1-\exp \left(-\frac{u t}{W}\right)\right]
\tag{16}
$$

